properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, rain, and strong southerly winds expected on Wednesday. Total snowfall amounts: 5 to 10 cm. Total rainfall amounts: 5 to 10 mm, except up to 15 mm along the southern shore. Maximum wind gusts: southerly generally between 60 to 80 km/h except 100 along parts of the coast. Time span: early Wednesday morning until Wednesday evening. Remarks: Strong southerly winds will accompany the snow causing a few hours of poor visibilities in snow and blowing snow over all areas on Wednesday morning. The snow will change to rain near noon or in the afternoon over all areas. Rain and mild temperatures have the potential to cause localized flooding and water pooling on roads. The public should prepare for poor travel conditions on Wednesday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy flurries this morning, then snow squalls this afternoon and tonight. Heavy flurries currently affecting the region will shift south out of the area this morning. These flurries will then intensify into snow squalls this morning. These snow squalls will shift northward near noon and then remain over the area through tonight. Additional flurries and local snow squalls will be possible Thursday. Snowfall amounts in the 10 to 15 cm range can be expected by Thursday morning. Visibilities will be reduced at times in heavy snow and blowing snow, particularly over exposed areas. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. An Arctic high exiting the Prairies will bring another cold morning to the region with extreme wind chill values. Temperatures near -30C combined with winds of 10 to 20 km/h will produce wind chills of -40 to -45 this morning. These extreme wind chills will moderate late this morning. Much warmer weather will spread across the Prairies through the second half of the week. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Santé at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Elevated pollution levels are expected or occurring. ROAD DUST ADVISORY IN EFFECT FOR VERNON (February 18, 2020 - Vernon) The Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy in collaboration with Interior Health has issued a Road Dust Advisory for Vernon because of high concentrations of coarse particulate matter that are expected to persist until there is precipitation or dust suppression. Levels tend to be highest around busy roads and industrial operations. This advisory is in effect until further notice. Persons with chronic underlying medical conditions should postpone strenuous exercise near busy roads until the advisory is lifted. Exposure is particularly a concern for infants, the elderly and those who have diabetes, and lung or heart disease. Real-time air quality observations and information regarding the health effects of air pollution can be found at https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. ### For more information on current air quality, visit www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

Description: Very strong wind gusts that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Strong southeast winds expected tonight. Maximum gusts: 150 km/h. Location: Margaree Harbour to Bay St. Lawrence. Time span: near midnight to early Wednesday morning. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may cause downed trees or toss loose objects. Les Suêtes wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible tonight through Wednesday night. With the arrival of cold northwesterly winds, snow squalls are forecast to develop late tonight. These snow squalls will continue through Wednesday before weakening Thursday morning. Locally heavy snowfall amounts will be possible with these snow squalls, as well as periods of reduced visibilities in heavy snow. Travellers are advised to consider changing their travel plans Wednesday. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. A frontal system will approach southern Alaska tonight bringing snow to the Haines - Skagway roads. Strong southerly winds will also be associated with this system. The strong winds will create blowing snow giving reduced visibilities. Conditions will improve Wednesday morning as the system moves to the east. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of about 15 cm is expected. Location: Victoria County Time span: Ending this morning. Remarks: Snow, heavy at times, will continue into this morning when a changeover to rain is expected. There is a slight risk of freezing rain during the changeover. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. An Arctic high exiting the Prairies will bring another cold morning to the region with extreme wind chill values. Temperatures near -30C combined with winds of 10 to 20 km/h will produce wind chills of -40 to -45 this morning. These extreme wind chills will moderate late this morning. Much warmer weather will spread across the Prairies through the second half of the week. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall, followed by significant rainfall, is expected. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm. Total rainfall: 20 to 30 mm. Locations: Burgeo and vicinity. Time span: late this morning to this afternoon. Remarks: Snow, at times heavy, will change to rain, at times heavy, by late this morning. The rain will taper off later this afternoon. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
